bio:
Prototyper and product designer.

I own a Taz 1.0 (og!), Creality CR-10, Mendelmax 1.5, Anet A8, and Im building one right now.

At school I run a CR-10 and 5 Makerbot Replicator Mini's. I also run the CNC, laser cutter, and vinyl plotter machines. At the other campus we have about 40 Afina Mini 3D printers.

At my last job I ran 8 Taz 4's, an oldschool lulz, a formlab, and created a photogrammy rig.

I consider myself a tinkerer? I see upgrades when i look at products and " what if's" while i try to think my way through a redesign or build. Solid works and Fusion are what I'm most familiar with. I have Fusion 360. I use Cura 4.3.0 for my slicer at home with my Tevo Tarantula. At work we are still using older version of Cura with a Ultimaker 3 Ext. At work we design fixtures and jigs for spray keep outs and manufacturing. At home i work on printing models for display, models I find on here. I design my own items for printing such as GPS mount for Snowmobile to brackets for printer, to pocket protectors to hold pens and tweezers.

I bought a FlashForge Creator Pro on a whim around the middle of 2016 without having many specific plans for it, but I haven't regretted it ever since. I use it together with Slic3r (and now its PrusaSlicer fork). If you want to try this yourself, I provide my PrusaSlicer configs and a lot of useful hints on my website.

My philosophy is simple: I solve my own problems and unless it is really something way too specific, I then share this solution such that others in the same situation do not need to go through the same problem-solving process all over again. I try to document everything from the viewpoint of someone unfamiliar with how I ended up with the solution. This is not always easy, hence some of the instructions will be incomplete or unclear. If you don't understand something, just ask, but keep in mind that you might be making me spend some additional free time on something I've already selflessly spent quite a bit of time on, so a bit of friendliness will go a long way.

If you browse through my Things, you'll find many remixes, most of which are improvements upon an existing model that I wasn't entirely happy with. If I notice a flaw or weakness in a model, I try to fix it and I share the improved model, again following the same philosophy I described above.

If you want to contact me to ask if you may sell prints of my models (most likely the Flexi Rex), please first read the description on the Thing page itself. The answer to your question is almost certainly in there.

If you like my models and download them for later, be sure to re-check if there is not an update before you start printing. I regularly improve upon the models and update the files with a new version. If there is something you think can be improved about a model, just ask, or remix it yourself!

And if you really like a model, tips are always appreciated! :) You can either use the ‘Tip designer’ button or one of the other tipping options mentioned on my website.

bio: I am not a clever man.

I was born and raised on the west coast of British Columbia, Canada . I've always loved arts and crafts. While growing up, I spend hours folding origami, sketching and even dabbled in graphic arts. Unfortunately, I lost the passion when I had to focus on my education and then carving out a successful career in the high tech industry.

In 2006, my husband and I were blessed with our first child. A few months into my maternity leave, I revived one of my long lost passions - origami. I took the time to teach myself how to build a simple website started an online Etsy store devoted to origami. This became a successful origami business for me.

In 2009, we were blessed with their second child. During my second maternity leave, it was a great opportunity to expand into illustrations. Started my focus on our second Etsy shop CindyHoDesigns.etsy.com.

Today, my focus is in arts and design. I've discovered the art of foil printing and cutting vinyl decals and loving the learning process.
